@page "/"

<PageTitle>dotcc — compile C &amp; Zig to .NET / WebAssembly, in your browser</PageTitle>

<section class="hero">
    <h1>Compile <span class="hl-c">C</span> and <span class="hl-zig">Zig</span> to <span class="hl-net">.NET&nbsp;/&nbsp;C#</span></h1>
    <p class="lede">
        <strong>dotcc</strong> is a clang-shaped compiler front-end that transpiles C — and
        Zig — to AOT-clean C&nbsp;14 on .NET&nbsp;10, with a second WebAssembly-text backend.
        Two languages, one typed IR, two back-ends. This whole page runs the <em>real</em>
        compiler, itself compiled to wasm, entirely in your browser tab.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="cta primary" href="sandbox">Open the sandbox →</a>
        <a class="cta" href="coverage">Browse coverage</a>
        <a class="cta ghost" href="https://github.com/sebgod/dotcc" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source on GitHub ↗</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="arch">
    <h2>N front-ends × M back-ends, meeting at one typed IR</h2>
    <div class="nm">
        <div class="nm-col">
            <span class="nm-label">front-ends</span>
            <div class="nm-node c">C</div>
            <div class="nm-node zig">Zig</div>
        </div>
        <div class="nm-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="nm-core">
            typed IR
            <small>a <code>CType</code> on every node</small>
        </div>
        <div class="nm-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="nm-col">
            <span class="nm-label">back-ends</span>
            <div class="nm-node net">C# / .NET</div>
            <div class="nm-node wat">WebAssembly</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <p class="arch-note">
        Each front-end lexes and parses its own LALR(1) grammar, then lowers into the
        <em>same</em> IR; every back-end realizes that one IR. No pairwise special-casing —
        today's 2×2 is C, Zig → C#, wat. Adding a language is a new front-end; adding a
        target is a new back-end. They meet in the middle.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="cards">
    <h2>Try it in the sandbox</h2>
    <div class="card-grid">
        <a class="card" href="@Deep("c", "Factorial")">
            <span class="card-tag c">C</span>
            <h3>Recursion &amp; printf</h3>
            <p>A recursive factorial with formatted output — compiled to wasm and run in-tab, stdout captured live.</p>
            <span class="card-go">Open →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="@Deep("c", "Primes")">
            <span class="card-tag c">C</span>
            <h3>Loops &amp; control flow</h3>
            <p>A prime sieve over nested <code>for</code> loops with <code>break</code> — the integer core the wat backend runs today.</p>
            <span class="card-go">Open →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="@Deep("zig", "Hello (std.debug.print)")">
            <span class="card-tag zig">Zig</span>
            <h3>std.debug.print</h3>
            <p>Idiomatic Zig — <code>while (i &lt;= n) : (i += 1)</code> and a curated <code>std.debug.print</code> writing to stderr.</p>
            <span class="card-go">Open →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="@Deep("zig", "Squares (extern printf)")">
            <span class="card-tag zig">Zig</span>
            <h3>C interop from Zig</h3>
            <p>A variadic <code>extern fn printf</code> — Zig lowering onto the same runtime the C front-end uses, output on stdout.</p>
            <span class="card-go">Open →</span>
        </a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="pipe">
    <h2>How a run works</h2>
    <p class="pipe-intro">
        Nothing leaves your browser. The C# back-end targets the CLR (a normal .NET program);
        the <strong>wat</strong> back-end is what makes execution possible here — a browser tab
        can run WebAssembly without a server, so the sandbox uses it end to end:
    </p>
    <ol class="pipe-steps">
        <li><span class="step-n">1</span> Your source is staged in an in-browser (MEMFS) filesystem.</li>
        <li><span class="step-n">2</span> dotcc — running as wasm — parses it and lowers to the typed IR.</li>
        <li><span class="step-n">3</span> The <code>wat</code> back-end emits WebAssembly text.</li>
        <li><span class="step-n">4</span> <code>wabt.js</code> assembles that text to a wasm module.</li>
        <li><span class="step-n">5</span> A tiny WASI shim runs <code>main()</code>, capturing stdout / stderr and the exit code.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="pipe-note">
        The <strong>C#</strong> and <strong>-E</strong> tabs in the sandbox show the same compile
        projected the other ways — the look-inside-the-compiler view.
    </p>
</section>

@code {
    /// <summary>Build a sandbox deep-link that pre-selects a language + starter example
    /// (read by <c>Sandbox.AdoptDeepLink</c>). The example name is URL-encoded so
    /// spaces / parens in names like "Hello (std.debug.print)" round-trip.</summary>
    private static string Deep(string lang, string example)
        => $"sandbox?lang={lang}&ex={Uri.EscapeDataString(example)}";
}
